<p>Convert and resizing images from the Linux terminal is as easy as installing
the <code class="highlighter-rouge">ImageMagick</code>. ImageMagick is a suite of command line utitlities for modifying and working with images.</p>

<h3 id="installation">Installation</h3>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nb">sudo </span>apt-get <span class="nb">install </span>imagemagick
</code></pre></div></div>
<h3 id="convert-between-formats">Convert between formats</h3>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>convert hello.png hello.jpg
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>specify a compression level for JPEG images</p>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>convert hello.png <span class="nt">-quality</span> 95 hello.jpg
</code></pre></div></div>

<h3 id="resize-an-image">Resize an image</h3>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>convert example.png <span class="nt">-resize</span> 200X100 example.png
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>ImageMagick overwrites original file if same file name used</p>

<p>ImageMagick tries to preserve the aspect ratio if you use this command. It will alter the image to fit within a 200x100 area, but the image wont be exacltly 200x100.</p>

<p>To force the image to have a specific size, execute</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>convert example.png <span class="nt">-resize</span> 200X100! example.png
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>The following resizes an image to a height of 100</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>convert example.png <span class="nt">-resize</span> x100 example.png
</code></pre></div></div>
